  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>For an apartment seller in Brisbane's inner east, the balcony or terrace is the feature buyers walk onto first, photograph mentally before they walk back inside, and remember most clearly when they decide whether to make an offer. It is also the feature most likely to produce hesitation if it is too shallow, too exposed, too hot, or poorly connected to the main living area. Floor area, kitchen finish, bedroom count, and parking matter, but in a like-for-like comparison between two apartments at a similar price point, the outdoor space is frequently the variable that decides which one trades faster and at a higher figure.</p>

      <p>This article walks through what genuinely makes a balcony or terrace work in Brisbane's climate, how buyers read outdoor space when they inspect, the dimensions and configurations that move price, and what an apartment seller can sensibly do to present the outdoor space at its best.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brisbane's climate makes outdoor space load-bearing</h2>
      <p>Brisbane has roughly nine months of useable outdoor weather a year. For an apartment buyer, the balcony or terrace is not an occasional bonus space; it is functionally an additional living room across most of the calendar. Buyers who are downsizing from a Queenslander with a verandah, a deck, or a back garden are particularly attuned to this. They are not looking for a token outdoor space that satisfies a development approval requirement; they are looking for a space that can hold a dining table, a couple of comfortable chairs, plants, and the routine of morning coffee or evening unwind without feeling cramped. An apartment that gives them that trades meaningfully better than one that does not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Depth is the single most important dimension</h2>
      <p>Balcony depth (the distance from the building line out to the balustrade) is the variable that determines whether the space is genuinely usable. A balcony that is 1.2 metres deep is largely a railing with a bit of standing room; you can put a single chair against the wall and squeeze past it. A balcony at 1.8 metres can hold a small bistro setting but feels tight when more than two people are using it. Balconies at 2.4 metres and above start to feel like rooms: a six-seat dining table fits comfortably, lounging is possible without anyone climbing over anyone else, and the space reads as part of the living layout rather than an annex to it. Buyers respond strongly to depth even when they do not consciously measure it. Width matters too, but depth is what unlocks usability.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Terraces add ground-level value, but with trade-offs</h2>
      <p>Ground floor and podium-level apartments often have terraces rather than balconies: larger, sometimes paved or grassed, with direct connection to gardens or common areas. For some buyers, especially those with small children or pets, a terrace is the dominant reason to choose an apartment with one over an elevated apartment without. The trade-off is privacy: terraces can be overlooked by passing residents, exposed to common-area noise, and visible from the street in ways that elevated balconies are not. The buyers who value terraces accept those trade-offs; the buyers who do not, will pay more for elevation and a balcony with similar usable area. Sellers should know which buyer their apartment is most attractive to and present it accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Orientation interacts with usability across the year</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane, a north-facing balcony or terrace gets winter sun into the apartment without absorbing the harshest western afternoon heat in summer. It is the orientation buyers ask about by name and pay a premium for. East-facing balconies catch morning sun and are shaded by midday, which suits people who use the space at breakfast. West-facing balconies cop the worst of summer afternoon sun and can be effectively unusable from December to February without significant shade or cooling intervention. South-facing balconies receive minimal direct sun and can feel cold in winter; in some apartments they are shaded enough year-round to be pleasant in summer but lifeless in cooler months. The orientation question is not theoretical; it shows up in price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Connection to the main living space</h2>
      <p>The way the balcony or terrace connects to the main internal space matters as much as the dimensions of the space itself. Stacker doors that fully retract, large bi-fold doors, or wide sliding doors that open the full width of the living area allow the inside and outside to function as one room. A single hinged door from a corner of the living area to a balcony does not, even if the balcony itself is well sized. Buyers walk through the apartment and form an impression of how they would actually use it: would they entertain across both spaces, would they leave the door open during the day, would the breeze flow through. Where the door geometry and orientation invite that flow, the whole apartment feels larger; where they do not, the balcony reads as separate from the main space, and value follows.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Privacy from neighbours and overlooking</h2>
      <p>Balconies in apartment buildings often sit close to neighbouring balconies on the same level or directly above and below. The degree of privacy: whether you can hold a conversation without it being overheard, whether you can sit outside in casual clothing without feeling watched, whether your neighbour's smoke or cooking smells reach you, makes a meaningful difference to whether the space is genuinely used or simply walked past. Buyers register privacy quickly during inspections, sometimes consciously and sometimes by feel. A balcony with frosted glass dividers, a strategic planting screen, a side wall that closes off one corner, or a layout that places it away from the busiest neighbour tends to feel materially better than one that is fully exposed to its neighbours.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Outlook and view: what is actually visible</h2>
      <p>The view from the balcony is part of what the buyer is buying. A view of the river, the city skyline, mature trees, a leafy street, or a quiet courtyard adds value; a view directly into a neighbouring building, onto a busy road, or over an air-conditioning plant subtracts from it. Brisbane's inner-east apartment stock varies enormously in this regard: two apartments in the same building, on the same floor, with the same internal layout, can have very different outlooks and trade at noticeably different prices because of it. Sellers cannot change the outlook, but they should price and present in a way that is honest about it. Photography that emphasises the best angle without misrepresenting the space tends to convert inspections into offers more reliably than photography that shows the outlook from a position no one would actually stand in.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Wind exposure on higher floors</h2>
      <p>Higher-floor apartments often have spectacular outlooks but can be wind-exposed in ways that make balcony use unpleasant. Brisbane's south-east winds in spring, the occasional storm-driven gust in summer, and prevailing breezes in winter can each render a higher-floor balcony unusable for hours or days at a time. Buyers who have lived in elevated apartments before know to ask about this; first-time apartment buyers often do not. A balcony with effective wind protection (glazed balustrades that extend higher than waist height, partial wall enclosures, careful aspect away from prevailing winds) functions across more of the year than one without. For sellers, an honest answer to a buyer's wind question, supported by lived experience of the space, is the right approach. Buyers who are surprised by wind after settlement become disgruntled owners and bad referrals.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Drainage, waterproofing, and the body corporate question</h2>
      <p>Balconies and terraces are the part of an apartment most exposed to weather, and they are the part most likely to develop drainage and waterproofing issues over time. A balcony with a noticeable slope away from the building, working drainage points that have been recently checked, and clear evidence of recent waterproofing is a different proposition to one with pooling water, stained tiling, or efflorescence on the underside of an upper-level balcony as seen from below. Buyers and their inspectors look at this carefully, and so should sellers in the lead-up to listing. Where a body corporate has recently completed a balcony rectification or waterproofing project across the building, that should be communicated as part of the campaign; where issues are known but not addressed, sellers should expect them to surface in the inspection report and price accordingly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Plants, furniture, and presentation for the campaign</h2>
      <p>Most apartment balconies are presented poorly during a sale campaign because sellers default to whatever furniture they happen to have. The balcony shows best with a small, well-proportioned outdoor setting that suggests a use case rather than crowding the space, a few healthy plants that bring colour and softness, and clear horizontal surfaces in the photographs. Oversized outdoor furniture that fills the balcony makes it look smaller; storage clutter, drying laundry, recycling bins, or unused barbecues read as excuses rather than features. For larger terraces, a deliberately styled zone (dining setting in one area, lounge setting in another) helps buyers picture how they would use the space rather than leaving them to work it out from an empty slab. Stylists who do this well in inner-east apartment campaigns tend to add more value than they cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can and cannot change before listing</h2>
      <p>Most of the variables that determine balcony or terrace value are fixed: depth, orientation, outlook, building design. What sellers can change in the lead-up to a campaign is presentation, drainage and waterproofing if there are addressable issues, planting, screening for privacy, lighting for evening photography, and the furniture used during inspections. These are usually low-cost interventions relative to the potential upside, and they tend to compound: a balcony that photographs well, looks usable at inspections, and feels private and protected on a hot afternoon is the balcony that converts inspection traffic into competing offers. For most apartment sellers in Brisbane's inner east, the outdoor space deserves more campaign attention than it tends to get.</p>

